  "prompt": "Can I glue a tooth filling back into my mouth?",
  "response": "It's not advisable to glue a tooth filling back into your mouth on your own. Dental fillings are placed and secured by dental professionals using specific materials and techniques to ensure they are properly bonded and safe. Here's what you should do instead:\n\n1. **Contact Your Dentist:** If a filling has come out, the first step is to call your dentist. They can assess the situation and schedule an appointment to replace the filling.\n\n2. **Temporary Measures:** If you can't see your dentist immediately and the area is sensitive, you can use over-the-counter dental cement or temporary filling material as a temporary fix. These products are available at pharmacies and are meant for short-term use until you can see a dentist.\n\n3. **Avoid DIY Solutions:** Using regular glue or other household adhesives is dangerous and can lead to further damage or health issues.\n\n4. **Maintain Oral Hygiene:** Keep the area clean and avoid chewing on the side of the missing filling to prevent further damage or discomfort.\n\nIt's important to address a lost filling promptly to prevent further dental issues such as tooth decay or sensitivity. Always consult a dental professional for proper treatment.",
